4. Terminology:
{
    "4. Terminology": [
        {
            "Original": "This section defines terminology specific to IPv6 and DHCP used in this document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models -> 6.4. DHCP for C:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.4. DHCP for Customer Edge Routers": [
        {
            "Original": "The DHCP requirements and network architecture for Customer Edge Routers are described in [RFC7084].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This model of operation combines address assignment (see Section 6.2) and prefix delegation (see Section 6.3).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In general, this model assumes that a single set of transactions between the client and server will assign or extend the client's non-temporary addresses and delegated prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

5. Client/Server Exchanges:
{
    "5. Client/Server Exchanges": [
        {
            "Original": "Clients and servers exchange DHCP messages using UDP (see [RFC768] and BCP 145 [RFC8085]).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client uses a link-local address or addresses determined through other mechanisms for transmitting and receiving DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A DHCP client sends most messages using a reserved, link-scoped multicast destination address so that the client need not be configured with the address or addresses of DHCP servers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To allow a DHCP client to send a message to a DHCP server that is not attached to the same link, a DHCP relay agent on the client's link will relay messages between the client and server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The operation of the relay agent is transparent to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The discussion of message exchanges in the remainder of this section will omit the description of the relaying of messages by relay agents.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Once the client has determined the address of a server, it may, under some circumstances, send messages directly to the server using unicast.",
            "Adjusted": "Once the DHCP client has determined the address of a DHCP server, the client may, under some circumstances, send messages directly to the server using unicast."
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models -> 6.5. DHCP for T:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.5. DHCP for Temporary Addresses": [
        {
            "Original": "Temporary addresses were originally introduced to avoid privacy concerns with stateless address autoconfiguration, which based 64 bits of the address on the EUI-64 (see [RFC4941].",
            "Adjusted": "Temporary addresses were originally introduced to avoid privacy concerns with stateless address autoconfiguration, which bases 64 bits of the address on the EUI-64 (see RFC4941)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "They were added to DHCP to provide complementary support when stateful address assignment is used.",
            "Adjusted": "Temporary addresses were added to DHCP to provide complementary support when stateful address assignment is used."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Temporary address assignment works mostly like non-temporary address assignment (see Section 6.2); however, these addresses are generally intended to be used for a short period of time and not to have their lifetimes extended, though they can be if required.",
            "Adjusted": "Temporary address assignment works mostly like non-temporary address assignment (see Section 6.2); however, temporary addresses are generally intended to be used for a short period of time and not to have their lifetimes extended, though they can be if required."
        }
    ]
}

5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.3. Serve:
{
    "5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.3. Server/Client Exchanges": [
        {
            "Original": "A server that has previously communicated with a client and negotiated for the client to listen for Reconfigure messages may send the client a Reconfigure message to initiate the client to update its configuration by sending an Information-request, Renew, or Rebind message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client then performs the two-message exchange as described earlier.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This can be used to expedite configuration changes to a client, such as the need to renumber a network (see [RFC6879]).",
            "Adjusted": "The Reconfigure message can be used to expedite configuration changes to a client, such as the need to renumber a network (see RFC6879)."
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models:
{
    "6. Operational Models": [
        {
            "Original": "This section describes some of the current most common DHCP operational models.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The described models are not mutually exclusive and are sometimes used together.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, a device may start in stateful mode to obtain an address and, at a later time when an application is started, request additional parameters using stateless mode.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This document assumes that the DHCP servers and the client, communicating with the servers via a specific interface, belong to a single provisioning domain.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "DHCP may be extended to support additional stateful services that may interact with one or more of the models described below.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Such interaction should be considered and documented as part of any future protocol extension.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants": [
        {
            "Original": "This section describes various program and networking constants used by DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants -> 7.2. UDP Ports:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants -> 7.2. UDP Ports": [
        {
            "Original": "Clients listen for DHCP messages on UDP port 546.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers and relay agents listen for DHCP messages on UDP port 547.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.2. Clien:
{
    "5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.2. Client/Server Exchanges Involving Four Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "To request the assignment of one or more addresses and/or delegated prefixes, a client first locates a DHCP server and then requests the assignment of addresses and/or delegated prefixes and other configuration information from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client sends a Solicit message to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address to find available DHCP servers.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Any server that can meet the client's requirements responds with an Advertise message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client then chooses one of the servers and sends a Request message to the server asking for confirmed assignment of addresses and/or delegated prefixes and other configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server responds with a Reply message that contains the confirmed addresses, delegated prefixes, and configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As described in the previous section, the client can request an extension of the lifetimes assigned to addresses or delegated prefixes (this is a two-message exchange).",
            "Adjusted": "As described in the previous section, the client can request an extension of the lifetimes assigned to addresses or delegated prefixes (the extension request is a two-message exchange)."
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models -> 6.1. Stateless:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.1. Stateless DHCP": [
        {
            "Original": "Stateless DHCP [RFC3736 Service for IPv6\"\")] is used when DHCP is not used for obtaining a lease but a node (DHCP client) desires one or more DHCP \"other configuration\" parameters, such as a list of DNS recursive name servers or DNS domain search lists [RFC3646\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "Stateless DHCP (RFC3736 Service for IPv6) is used when DHCP is not used for obtaining a lease but a node (DHCP client) desires one or more DHCP \"other configuration\" parameters, such as a list of DNS recursive name servers or DNS domain search lists (RFC3646)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Stateless DHCP may be used when a node initially boots or at any time the software on the node requires some missing or expired configuration information that is available via DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is the simplest and most basic operation for DHCP and requires a client (and a server) to support only two messages -- Information-request and Reply.",
            "Adjusted": "Stateless DHCP is the simplest and most basic operation for DHCP and requires a client (and a server) to support only two messages: Information-request and Reply."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that DHCP servers and relay agents typically also need to support the Relay-forward and Relay-reply messages to accommodate operation when clients and servers are not on the same link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants -> 7.4. DHCP Option Co:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants -> 7.4. DHCP Option Codes": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP makes extensive use of options in messages; some of these are defined later, inSection 21.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP makes extensive use of options in messages; some of these options are defined later, in Section 21."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Additional options are defined in other documents or may be defined in the future (see [RFC7227] for guidance on new option definitions).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants -> 7.5. Status Codes:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants -> 7.5. Status Codes": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP uses status codes to communicate the success or failure of operations requested in messages from clients and servers and to provide additional information about the specific cause of the failure of a message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The specific status codes are defined inSection 21.13.",
            "Adjusted": "The specific status codes are defined in Section 21.13."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Status Code option (see Section 21.13) does not appear in a message in which the option could appear, the status of the message is assumed to be Success.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models -> 6.2. DHCP for N:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.2. DHCP for Non-temporary Address Assignment": [
        {
            "Original": "This model of operation was the original motivation for DHCP.",
            "Adjusted": "The model of operation for non-temporary address assignment was the original motivation for DHCP."
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is appropriate for situations where stateless address autoconfiguration alone is insufficient or impractical, e.g., because of network policy, additional requirements such as dynamic updates to the DNS, or client-specific requirements.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP for non-temporary address assignment is appropriate for situations where stateless address autoconfiguration alone is insufficient or impractical, e.g., because of network policy, additional requirements such as dynamic updates to the DNS, or client-specific requirements."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The model of operation for non-temporary address assignment is as follows.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server is provided with prefixes from which it may allocate addresses to clients, as well as any related network topology information as to which prefixes are present on which links.",
            "Adjusted": "The DHCP server is provided with prefixes from which it may allocate addresses to clients, as well as any related network topology information as to which prefixes are present on which links."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client requests a non-temporary address to be assigned by the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server allocates an address or addresses appropriate for the link on which the client is connected.",
            "Adjusted": "The DHCP server allocates an address or addresses appropriate for the link on which the client is connected."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server returns the allocated address or addresses to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "The DHCP server returns the allocated address or addresses to the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each address has associated preferred and valid lifetimes, which constitute an agreement about the length of time over which the client is allowed to use the address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can request an extension of the lifetimes on an address and is required to terminate the use of an address if the valid lifetime of the address expires.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Typically, clients request other configuration parameters, such as the DNS name server addresses and domain search lists, when requesting addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients can also request more than one address or set of addresses (see Sections6.6 and 12).",
            "Adjusted": "Clients can also request more than one address or set of addresses (see Sections 6.6 and 12)."
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants -> 7.1. Multicast Addr:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants -> 7.1. Multicast Addresses": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP makes use of the following multicast addresses: All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers (ff02::1:2) A link-scoped multicast address used by a client to communicate with neighboring (i.e., on-link) relay agents and servers.",
            "Adjusted": "DHCP makes use of the following multicast addresses: All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers (ff02::1:2) is a link-scoped multicast address used by a client to communicate with neighboring (i.e., on-link) relay agents and servers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "All servers and relay agents are members of this multicast group.",
            "Adjusted": "All servers and relay agents are members of this multicast group."
        },
        {
            "Original": "All_DHCP_Servers (ff05::1:3) A site-scoped multicast address used by a relay agent to communicate with servers, either because the relay agent wants to send messages to all servers or because it does not know the unicast addresses of the servers.",
            "Adjusted": "All_DHCP_Servers (ff05::1:3) is a site-scoped multicast address used by a relay agent to communicate with servers, either because the relay agent wants to send messages to all servers or because the relay agent does not know the unicast addresses of the servers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Note that in order for a relay agent to use this address, it must have an address of sufficient scope to be reachable by the servers.",
            "Adjusted": "Note that in order for a relay agent to use this address, the relay agent must have an address of sufficient scope to be reachable by the servers."
        },
        {
            "Original": "All servers within the site are members of this multicast group on the interfaces that are within the site.",
            "Adjusted": "All servers within the site are members of this multicast group on the interfaces that are within the site."
        }
    ]
}

7. DHCP Constants -> 7.7. Representation:
{
    "7. DHCP Constants -> 7.7. Representation of Time Values and \"Infinity\" as a Time Value": [
        {
            "Original": "All time values for lifetimes, T1, and T2 are unsigned 32-bit integers and are expressed in units of seconds.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The value 0xffffffff is taken to mean \"infinity\" when used as a lifetime (as in [RFC4861\"\"]) or a value for T1 or T2.",
            "Adjusted": "The value 0xffffffff is taken to mean \"infinity\" when used as a lifetime (as in RFC4861) or a value for T1 or T2."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Setting the valid lifetime of an address or a delegated prefix to 0xffffffff (\"infinity\") amounts to a permanent assignment of an address or delegation to a client and should only be used in cases where permanent assignments are desired.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Care should be taken in setting T1 or T2 to 0xffffffff (\"infinity\").",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client will never attempt to extend the lifetimes of any addresses in an IA with T1 set to 0xffffffff.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client will never attempt to use a Rebind message to locate a different server to extend the lifetimes of any addresses in an IA with T2 set to 0xffffffff.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.1. Clien:
{
    "5. Client/Server Exchanges -> 5.1. Client/Server Exchanges Involving Two Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "When a DHCP client does not need to have a DHCP server assign IP addresses or delegated prefixes to it, the client can obtain other configuration information such as a list of available DNS servers [RFC3646\"\")] or NTP servers [RFC5908 Server Option for DHCPv6\"\")] through a single message and reply exchange with a DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "When a DHCP client does not need to have a DHCP server assign IP addresses or delegated prefixes to it, the client can obtain other configuration information such as a list of available DNS servers (RFC3646) or NTP servers (RFC5908 Server Option for DHCPv6) through a single message and reply exchange with a DHCP server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "To obtain other configuration information, the client first sends an Information-request message to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Servers respond with a Reply message containing the other configuration information for the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client may also request the server to expedite address assignment and/or prefix delegation by using a two-message exchange instead of the normal four-message exchange as discussed in the next section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Expedited assignment can be requested by the client, and servers may or may not honor the request (see Sections 18.3.1 and 21.14 for more details and why servers may not honor this request).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Clients may request this expedited service in environments where it is likely that there is only one server available on a link and no expectation that a second server would become available, or when completing the configuration process as quickly as possible is a priority.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To request the expedited two-message exchange, the client sends a Solicit message to the All_DHCP_Relay_Agents_and_Servers multicast address requesting the assignment of addresses and/or delegated prefixes and other configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This message includes an indication (the Rapid Commit option; see Section 21.14) that the client is willing to accept an immediate Reply message from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server that is willing to commit the assignment of addresses and/or delegated prefixes to the client immediately responds with a Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The configuration information and the addresses and/or delegated prefixes in the Reply message are then immediately available for use by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each address or delegated prefix assigned to the client has associated preferred and valid lifetimes specified by the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To request an extension of the lifetimes assigned to an address or delegated prefix, the client sends a Renew message to the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server sends a Reply message to the client with the new lifetimes, allowing the client to continue to use the address or delegated prefix without interruption.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is unable to extend the lifetime of an address or delegated prefix, it indicates this by returning the address or delegated prefix with lifetimes of 0\\.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server is unable to extend the lifetime of an address or delegated prefix, the server indicates this by returning the address or delegated prefix with lifetimes of 0."
        },
        {
            "Original": "At the same time, the server may assign other addresses or delegated prefixes.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "See Section 18 for descriptions of additional two-message exchanges between the client and server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

6. Operational Models -> 6.6. Multiple A:
{
    "6. Operational Models -> 6.6. Multiple Addresses and Prefixes": [
        {
            "Original": "DHCP allows a client to receive multiple addresses.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "During typical operation, a client sends one instance of an IA_NA option and the server assigns at most one address from each prefix assigned to the link to which the client is attached.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In particular, the server can be configured to serve addresses out of multiple prefixes for a given link.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is useful in cases such as when a network renumbering event is in progress.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In a typical deployment, the server will grant one address for each IA_NA option (see Section 21.4).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can explicitly request multiple addresses by sending multiple IA_NA options (and/or IA_TA options; see Section 21.5).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client can send multiple IA_NA (and/or IA_TA) options in its initial transmissions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Alternatively, it can send an extra Request message with additional new IA_NA (and/or IA_TA) options (or include them in a Renew message).",
            "Adjusted": "Alternatively, the client can send an extra Request message with additional new IA_NA (and/or IA_TA) options (or include them in a Renew message)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The same principle also applies to prefix delegation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In principle, DHCP allows a client to request new prefixes to be delegated by sending additional IA_PD options (see Section 21.21).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, a typical operator usually prefers to delegate a single, larger prefix.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In most deployments, it is recommended that the client request a larger prefix in its initial transmissions rather than request additional prefixes later on.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The exact behavior of the server (whether to grant additional addresses and prefixes or not) is up to the server policy and is out of scope for this document.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For more information on how the server distinguishes between IA option instances, see Section 12.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

10. Representation and Use of Domain Nam:
{
    "10. Representation and Use of Domain Names": [
        {
            "Original": "So that domain names may be encoded uniformly, a domain name or a list of domain names is encoded using the technique described in[Section 3.1 of [RFC1035]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc1035#section-3.1).",
            "Adjusted": "So that domain names may be encoded uniformly, a domain name or a list of domain names is encoded using the technique described in Section 3.1 of RFC1035."
