            "Original": "The relay agent copies the received DHCP message (excluding any IP or UDP headers) into a Relay Message option (see Section 21.10) in the new message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The relay agent adds to the Relay-forward message any other options it is configured to include.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "[RFC6221] defines a Lightweight DHCPv6 Relay Agent (LDRA) that allows relay agent information to be inserted by an access node that performs a link-layer bridging (i.e., non-routing) function.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.1. Relaying a Client Message or a Relay-forward Message -> 19.1.3. Relay Agent Behavior with Prefix Delegation": [
        {
            "Original": "A relay agent forwards messages containing prefix delegation options in the same way as it would relay addresses (i.e., per Sections19.1.1 and 19.1.2).",
            "Adjusted": "A relay agent forwards messages containing prefix delegation options in the same way as the relay agent would relay addresses (i.e., per Sections 19.1.1 and 19.1.2)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If a server communicates with a client through a relay agent about delegated prefixes, the server may need a protocol or other out-of-band communication to configure routing information for delegated prefixes on any router through which the client may forward traffic.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "This document introduces two security mechanisms for the authentication of DHCP messages: (1) authentication (and encryption) of messages sent between servers and relay agents using IPsec and (2) protection against misconfiguration of a client caused by a Reconfigure message sent by a malicious DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The delayed authentication protocol, defined in [RFC3315\"\")], has been obsoleted by this document (see Section 25).",
            "Adjusted": "The delayed authentication protocol, defined in RFC3315, has been obsoleted by this document (see Section 25)."
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 2:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.1. Security of Messages Sent between Servers and Relay Agents": [
        {
            "Original": "Relay agents and servers that exchange messages can use IPsec as detailed in [RFC8213].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.1. Relayi:
{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.1. Relaying a Client Message or a Relay-forward Message -> 19.1.2. Relaying a Message from a Relay Agent": [
        {
            "Original": "If the message received by the relay agent is a Relay-forward message and the hop-count value in the message is greater than or equal to HOP_COUNT_LIMIT, the relay agent discards the received message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The relay agent copies the source address from the IP datagram in which the message was received into the peer-address field in the Relay-forward message and sets the hop-count field to the value of the hop-count field in the received message incremented by 1.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the source address from the IP datagram header of the received message is a globally scoped unicast address (i.e., GUA or ULA), the relay agent sets the link-address field to 0; otherwise, the relay agent sets the link-address field to a globally scoped unicast address (i.e., GUA or ULA) assigned to the interface on which the message was received or includes an Interface-Id option (seeSection 21.18) to identify the interface on which the message was received.",
            "Adjusted": "If the source address from the IP datagram header of the received message is a globally scoped unicast address (i.e., GUA or ULA), the relay agent sets the link-address field to 0; otherwise, the relay agent sets the link-address field to a globally scoped unicast address (i.e., GUA or ULA) assigned to the interface on which the message was received or includes an Interface-Id option (see Section 21.18) to identify the interface on which the message was received."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.1. Relaying a Client Message or a Relay-forward Message -> 19.1.1. Relaying a Message from a Client": [
        {
            "Original": "If the relay agent received the message to be relayed from a client, the relay agent places a globally scoped unicast address (i.e., GUA or ULA) from a prefix assigned to the link on which the client should be assigned leases into the link-address field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If such an address is not available, the relay agent may set the link-address field to a link-local address from the interface on which the original message was received.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This is not recommended, as it may require that additional information be provided in the server configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "Setting the link-address field to a link-local address is not recommended, as it may require that additional information be provided in the server configuration."
        },
        {
            "Original": "See[Section 3.2 of [RFC7969]](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7969#section-3.2) for a detailed discussion.",
            "Adjusted": "See Section 3.2 of RFC7969 for a detailed discussion."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This address will be used by the server to determine the link from which the client should be assigned leases and other configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "The address in the link-address field will be used by the server to determine the link from which the client should be assigned leases and other configuration information."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The hop-count value in the Relay-forward message is set to 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the relay agent cannot use the address in the link-address field to identify the interface through which the response to the client will be relayed, the relay agent MUST include an Interface-Id option (see Section 21.18) in the Relay-forward message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server will include the Interface-Id option in its Relay-reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The relay agent sets the link-address field as described earlier in this subsection, regardless of whether the relay agent includes an Interface-Id option in the Relay-forward message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.2. Relayi:
{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.2. Relaying a Relay-reply Message": [
        {
            "Original": "The relay agent processes any options included in the Relay-reply message in addition to the Relay Message option (seeSection 21.10).",
            "Adjusted": "The relay agent processes any options included in the Relay-reply message in addition to the Relay Message option (see Section 21.10)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The relay agent extracts the message from the Relay Message option and relays it to the address contained in the peer-address field of the Relay-reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Relay agents MUST NOT modify the message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the Relay-reply message includes an Interface-Id option (see Section 21.18), the relay agent relays the message from the server to the client on the link identified by the Interface-Id option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise, if the link-address field is not set to 0, the relay agent relays the message on the link identified by the link-address field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the relay agent receives a Relay-reply message, it MUST process the message as defined above, regardless of the type of message encapsulated in the Relay Message option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3. Server Behavior -> 18.3.11. Creation and Transmission of Reconfigure Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "The server sets the \"msg-type\" field to RECONFIGURE and sets the \"transaction-id\" field to 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes a Server Identifier option (seeSection 21.3) containing its DUID and a Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) containing the client's DUID in the Reconfigure message.",
            "Adjusted": "The server includes a Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3) containing its DUID and a Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) containing the client's DUID in the Reconfigure message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Because of the risk of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks against DHCP clients, the use of a security mechanism is mandated in Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST use DHCP authentication in the Reconfigure message (see Section 20.4).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST include a Reconfigure Message option (see Section 21.19) to select whether the client responds with a Renew message, a Rebind message, or an Information-request message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST NOT include any other options in the Reconfigure message, except as specifically allowed in the definition of individual options.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A server sends each Reconfigure message to a single DHCP client, using an IPv6 unicast address of sufficient scope belonging to the DHCP client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server does not have an address to which it can send the Reconfigure message directly to the client, the server uses a Relay-reply message (as described in Section 19.3) to send the Reconfigure message to a relay agent that will relay the message to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server may obtain the address of the client (and the appropriate relay agent, if required) through the information the server has about clients that have been in contact with the server (see Section 18.3) or through some external agent.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To reconfigure more than one client, the server unicasts a separate message to each client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server may initiate the reconfiguration of multiple clients concurrently; for example, a server may send a Reconfigure message to additional clients while previous reconfiguration message exchanges are still in progress.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Reconfigure message causes the client to initiate a Renew/Reply, Rebind/Reply, or Information-request/Reply message exchange with the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server interprets the receipt of a Renew, Rebind, or Information-request message (whichever was specified in the original Reconfigure message) from the client as satisfying the Reconfigure message request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When transmitting the Reconfigure message, the server sets the retransmission time (RT) to REC_TIMEOUT.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server does not receive a Renew, Rebind, or Information-request message from the client before the RT elapses, the server retransmits the Reconfigure message, doubles the RT value, and waits again.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server continues this process until REC_MAX_RC unsuccessful attempts have been made, at which point the server SHOULD abort the reconfigure process for that client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Default and initial values for REC_TIMEOUT and REC_MAX_RC are documented in Section 7.6.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 2:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.4. Reconfiguration Key Authentication Protocol (RKAP)": [
        {
            "Original": "RKAP provides protection against misconfiguration of a client caused by a Reconfigure message sent by a malicious DHCP server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this protocol, a DHCP server sends a reconfigure key to the client in the initial exchange of DHCP messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client records the reconfigure key for use in authenticating subsequent Reconfigure messages from that server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server then includes a Hashed Message Authentication Code (HMAC) computed from the reconfigure key in subsequent Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Both the reconfigure key sent from the server to the client and the HMAC in subsequent Reconfigure messages are carried as the authentication information in an Authentication option (seeSection 21.11).",
            "Adjusted": "Both the reconfigure key sent from the server to the client and the HMAC in subsequent Reconfigure messages are carried as the authentication information in an Authentication option (see Section 21.11)."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The format of the authentication information is defined in the following section.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "RKAP is used (initiated by the server) only if the client and server have negotiated to use Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.4. Reconfiguration Key Authentication Protocol (RKAP) -> 20.4.3. Client Considerations for RKAP": [
        {
            "Original": "The client will receive a reconfigure key from the server in an Authentication option (seeSection 21.11) in the initial Reply message from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "The client will receive a reconfigure key from the server in an Authentication option (see Section 21.11) in the initial Reply message from the server."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The client records the reconfigure key for use in authenticating subsequent Reconfigure messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To authenticate a Reconfigure message, the client computes an HMAC-MD5 over the Reconfigure message, with zeroes substituted for the HMAC-MD5 field, using the reconfigure key received from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this computed HMAC-MD5 matches the value in the Authentication option, the client accepts the Reconfigure message.",
            "Adjusted": "If the computed HMAC-MD5 matches the value in the Authentication option, the client accepts the Reconfigure message."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.2. Summary of DHCP Authentication": [
        {"Original": "Authentication of DHCP messages is accomplished through the use of the Authentication option (seeSection 21.11).", "Adjusted": "Authentication of DHCP messages is accomplished through the use of the Authentication option (see Section 21.11)."},
        {"Original": "The authentication information carried in the Authentication option can be used to reliably identify the source of a DHCP message and to confirm that the contents of the DHCP message have not been tampered with.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "The Authentication option provides a framework for multiple authentication protocols.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "One such protocol, RKAP, is defined in Section 20.4.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "Other protocols defined in the future will be specified in separate documents.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "Any DHCP message MUST NOT include more than one Authentication option.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "The protocol field in the Authentication option identifies the specific protocol used to generate the authentication information carried in the option.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "The algorithm field identifies a specific algorithm within the authentication protocol; for example, the algorithm field specifies the hash algorithm used to generate the Message Authentication Code (MAC) in the Authentication option.", "Adjusted": "No change"},
        {"Original": "The RDM field specifies the type of replay detection used in the replay detection field.", "Adjusted": "No change"}
    ]
}

{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.4. Reconfiguration Key Authentication Protocol (RKAP) -> 20.4.2. Server Considerations for RKAP": [
        {
            "Original": "The server selects a reconfigure key for a client during the Request/Reply, Solicit/Reply, or Information-request/Reply message exchange.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server records the reconfigure key and transmits that key to the client in an Authentication option (seeSection 21.11) in the Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "The server records the reconfigure key and transmits the reconfigure key to the client in an Authentication option (see Section 21.11) in the Reply message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The reconfigure key is 128 bits long and MUST be a cryptographically strong random or pseudorandom number that cannot easily be predicted.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "To provide authentication for a Reconfigure message, the server selects a replay detection value according to the RDM selected by the server and computes an HMAC-MD5 of the Reconfigure message using the reconfigure key for the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server computes the HMAC-MD5 over the entire DHCP Reconfigure message, including the Authentication option; the HMAC-MD5 field in the Authentication option is set to 0 for the HMAC-MD5 computation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes the HMAC-MD5 in the authentication information field in an Authentication option included in the Reconfigure message sent to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3:
{
    "18. DHCP Configuration Exchanges -> 18.3. Server Behavior -> 18.3.5. Receipt of Rebind Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "SeeSection 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Rebind messages received via unicast.",
            "Adjusted": "See Section 18.4 for details regarding the handling of Rebind messages received via unicast."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Unicast transmission of Rebind messages is not allowed, regardless of whether the Server Unicast option (see Section 21.12) is configured or not.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the server receives a Rebind message that contains an IA option from a client, it locates the client's binding and verifies that the information in the IA from the client matches the information stored for that client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server finds the client entry for the IA and the server determines that the addresses or delegated prefixes in the IA are appropriate for the link to which the client's interface is attached according to the server's explicit configuration information, the server SHOULD send the IA back to the client with new lifetimes and, if applicable, T1/T2 values.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is unable to extend the lifetimes of an address in the IA, the server MAY choose not to include the IA Address option (see Section 21.6) for this address.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server is unable to extend the lifetimes of a delegated prefix in the IA, the server MAY choose not to include the IA Prefix option (see Section 21.22) for this prefix.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server finds that the client entry for the IA and any of the addresses or delegated prefixes are no longer appropriate for the link to which the client's interface is attached according to the server's explicit configuration information, the server returns those addresses or delegated prefixes to the client with lifetimes of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server cannot find a client entry for the IA, the server checks if the IA contains addresses (for IA_NAs and IA_TAs) or delegated prefixes (for IA_PDs).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server checks if the addresses and delegated prefixes are appropriate for the link to which the client's interface is attached according to the server's explicit configuration information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For any address that is not appropriate for the link to which the client's interface is attached, the server MAY include the IA Address option with lifetimes of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For any delegated prefix that is not appropriate for the link to which the client's interface is attached, the server MAY include the IA Prefix option with lifetimes of 0.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The Reply with lifetimes of 0 constitutes an explicit notification to the client that the specific addresses and delegated prefixes are no longer valid and MUST NOT be used by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the server chooses to not include any IAs containing IA Address or IA Prefix options with lifetimes of 0 and the server does not include any other IAs with leases and/or status codes, the server does not send a Reply message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this situation, the server discards the Rebind message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Otherwise, for each IA for which the server cannot find a client entry, the server has the following choices, depending on the server's policy and configuration information: \\- If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Rebind messages (also see the note below about the Rapid Commit option (Section 21.14)), the server SHOULD create a binding and return the IA with allocated leases with lifetimes and, if applicable, T1/T2 values and other information requested by the client.",
            "Adjusted": "Otherwise, for each IA for which the server cannot find a client entry, the server has the following choices, depending on the server's policy and configuration information: If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Rebind messages (also see the note below about the Rapid Commit option (Section 21.14)), the server SHOULD create a binding and return the IA with allocated leases with lifetimes and, if applicable, T1/T2 values and other information requested by the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST NOT return any addresses or delegated prefixes in the IA that the server does not assign to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Rebind messages but the server will not assign any leases to an IA, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) with the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code and a status message for a user.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server is configured to create new bindings as a result of processing Rebind messages but the server will not assign any leases to an IA, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option (see Section 21.13) with the NoAddrsAvail or NoPrefixAvail status code and a status message for a user."
        },
        {
            "Original": "\\- If the server does not support creation of new bindings for the client sending a Rebind message or if this behavior is disabled according to the server's policy or configuration information, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option with the NoBinding status code and a status message for a user.",
            "Adjusted": "If the server does not support creation of new bindings for the client sending a Rebind message or if this behavior is disabled according to the server's policy or configuration information, the server returns the IA option containing a Status Code option with the NoBinding status code and a status message for a user."
        },
        {
            "Original": "When the server creates new bindings for the IA, it is possible that other servers also create bindings as a result of receiving the same Rebind message; see the \"DISCUSSION\" text in Section 21.14.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Therefore, the server SHOULD only create new bindings during processing of a Rebind message if the server is configured to respond with a Reply message to a Solicit message containing the Rapid Commit option.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server constructs a Reply message by setting the \"msg-type\" field to REPLY and copying the transaction ID from the Rebind message into the \"transaction-id\" field.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST include in the Reply message a Server Identifier option (see Section 21.3) containing the server's DUID and the Client Identifier option (see Section 21.2) from the Rebind message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server includes other options containing configuration information to be returned to the client as described in Section 18.3.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MAY include options containing the IAs and values for other configuration parameters, even if those IAs and parameters were not requested in the Rebind message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The T1 or T2 values set in each applicable IA option for a Reply MUST be the same values across all IAs.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server MUST determine the T1 or T2 values across all of the applicable client's bindings in the Reply.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This facilitates the client being able to renew all of the bindings at the same time.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.3. Constr:
{
    "19. Relay Agent Behavior -> 19.3. Construction of Relay-reply Messages": [
        {
            "Original": "A server uses a Relay-reply message to (1) return a response to a client if the original message from the client was relayed to the server in a Relay-forward message or (2) send a Reconfigure message to a client if the server does not have an address it can use to send the message directly to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A response to the client MUST be relayed through the same relay agents as the original client message.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server causes this to happen by creating a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option (seeSection 21.10) containing the message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "The server causes the response to be relayed through the same relay agents by creating a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option (see Section 21.10) containing the message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The contained Relay-reply message contains another Relay Message option to be sent to the next relay agent, and so on.",
            "Adjusted": "The contained Relay-reply message contains another Relay Message option to be sent to the next relay agent, and so on."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server must record the contents of the peer-address fields in the received message so it can construct the appropriate Relay-reply message carrying the response from the server.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, if client C sent a message that was relayed by relay agent A to relay agent B and then to the server, the server would send the following Relay-reply message to relay agent B: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 1 link-address: 0 peer-address: A Relay Message option containing the following: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 0 link-address: address from link to which C is attached peer-address: C Relay Message option: <response from server> Figure 10: Relay-reply Example When sending a Reconfigure message to a client through a relay agent, the server creates a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option containing the Reconfigure message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "For example, if client C sent a message that was relayed by relay agent A to relay agent B and then to the server, the server would send the following Relay-reply message to relay agent B: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 1 link-address: 0 peer-address: A Relay Message option containing the following: msg-type: RELAY-REPL hop-count: 0 link-address: address from link to which C is attached peer-address: C Relay Message option: <response from server>. When sending a Reconfigure message to a client through a relay agent, the server creates a Relay-reply message that includes a Relay Message option containing the Reconfigure message for the next relay agent in the return path to the client."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server sets the peer-address field in the Relay-reply message header to the address of the client and sets the link-address field as required by the relay agent to relay the Reconfigure message to the client.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The server obtains the addresses of the client and the relay agent through prior interaction with the client or through some external mechanism.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 2:
{
    "20. Authentication of DHCP Messages -> 20.3. Replay Detection": [
        {
            "Original": "The RDM field of the Authentication option (seeSection 21.11) determines the type of replay detection used in the replay detection field.",
            "Adjusted": "The RDM field of the Authentication option (see Section 21.11) determines the type of replay detection used in the replay detection field."
        },
        {
            "Original": "If the RDM field contains 0x00, the replay detection field MUST be set to the value of a strictly monotonically increasing 64-bit unsigned integer (modulo 2^64).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Using this technique can reduce the danger of replay attacks.",
            "Adjusted": "Using the replay detection technique can reduce the danger of replay attacks."
        },
        {
            "Original": "This method MUST be supported by all Authentication option protocols.",
            "Adjusted": "The replay detection method MUST be supported by all Authentication option protocols."
        },
        {
            "Original": "One choice might be to use the 64-bit NTP timestamp format [RFC5905]).",
            "Adjusted": "One choice might be to use the 64-bit NTP timestamp format [RFC5905]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A client that receives a message with the RDM field set to 0x00 MUST compare its replay detection field with the previous value sent by that same server (based on the Server Identifier option; see Section 21.3) and only accept the message if the received value is greater and record this as the new value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "If this is the first time a client processes an Authentication option sent by a server, the client MUST record the replay detection value and skip the replay detection check.",
